'''{{Nihongo|Kagi Shrine|嘉義神社|Kagi jinja|lead=yes}}''' was a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in previously ''Soa-a-teng'' ({{zh|t=山仔頂|poj=Soaⁿ-á-téng}}), Kagi City, {{ill|Tainan Prefecture|en|Tainan Prefecture|qid=Q697894|lt=Tainan Prefecture|1=Tainan Prefecture}}, {{ill|Taiwan under Japanese rule|en|Taiwan under Japanese rule|qid=Q137816|lt=Japanese Taiwan|1=Taiwan under Japanese rule}} (modern-day {{ill|Chiayi Park|en|Chiayi Park|qid=Q10924084|lt=Chiayi Park|1=Chiayi Park}}, [[Chiayi|Chiayi City]], {{ill|Taiwan|en|Taiwan|qid=Q865|lt=Taiwan|1=Taiwan}}).
The shrine was built on 28 October 1915 ({{ill|Taishō era|en|Taishō era|qid=Q329174|lt=Taishō|1=Taishō era}} 4) facing south but later altered in 1942 ({{ill|Shōwa era|en|Shōwa era|qid=Q327567|lt=Shōwa|1=Shōwa era}} 17) to face west. The shrine was originally categorized as a prefectural shrine in 1917 ({{ill|Taishō era|en|Taishō era|qid=Q329174|lt=Taishō|1=Taishō era}} 6) but elevated to Rank of {{nihongo4|small shrine|国幣小社|[[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|Kokuhei-shōsha]]}} in 1944 ({{ill|Shōwa era|en|Shōwa era|qid=Q327567|lt=Shōwa|1=Shōwa era}} 19). [[:en:Prince Yoshihisa|Prince Yoshihisa]], {{nihongo4||大国魂命|Ōkunitama no Mikoto}}, [[Ōkuninushi|Ōnamuchi no Mikoto]], {{nihongo4||少彦名命|Sukunahikona no Mikoto}} and [[Amaterasu]] were enshrined as deities.
The ''[[honden]]'' (main hall) was turned into a {{ill|Martyrs' shrines (China)|en|Martyrs' shrines (China)|qid=Q6800982|lt=martyrs' shrine|1=Martyrs' shrines (China)}} by the [[:en:Republic of China|Republic of China]] government after World War II but was destroyed in a fire on 24 April 1994. The main office and purification hall now serve as the '''Chiayi City Historical Relics Museum'''.
In 1998 the [[:en:Chiayi Tower|Chiayi Tower]] was built in place of the main hall, the design was inspired by an [[:en:Taiwanese aborigines|indigenous]] mythological tale about the creator of the world. In Chinese the tower is called {{ill|Sun-Shooting Tower|en|Sun-Shooting Tower|qid=Q10957191|lt=Sun-Shooting Tower|1=Sun-Shooting Tower}} and houses an observation deck.
The existing {{nihongo4|main office|社務所|shamusho}} and {{nihongo4|purification hall|斎館|saikan}} are wooden structures built in the classical Japanese {{ill|Shoin-zukuri|en|Shoin-zukuri|qid=Q2576209|lt=Shoin-zukuri|1=Shoin-zukuri}} architectural style and underwent repair work before being opened to the general public on 5 January 2001 as the '''Chiayi City Historical Relics Museum'''. The area became part of Chiayi Park and the {{ill|Chōzuya|en|Chōzuya|qid=Q1069667|lt=Chōzuya|1=Chōzuya}} (purification pavilion), {{ill|Sandō|en|Sandō|qid=Q667783|lt=Sandō|1=Sandō}} (pathway), {{ill|Stone lantern|en|Stone lantern|qid=Q12012294|lt=stone tōrō lantern|1=Stone lantern}}, and {{ill|Komainu|en|Komainu|qid=Q20155846|lt=Komainu|1=Komainu}} statues amongst other things still exist today.
